refactor(backend): Change Prompt from record to class and update data access

Refactors the `Prompt` domain object from a Java Record to a Class to support mutability for updates. Adds `conversationId` and `response` fields. The `PromptRepository` is changed to an interface to decouple it from the specific data store, improving flexibility for future storage options.

feat(chrome-extension): Refactor to intercept network requests

Overhauls the data capture mechanism from DOM scraping to intercepting fetch/XHR network requests. This allows for more reliable capture of prompt and response data, including conversation IDs. The manifest is updated with necessary permissions (`webRequest`, `webRequestBlocking`), and the logic is split between a content script and an injected main-world script to access page APIs.

feat(frontend): Implement conversation view and search page

Adds a new Search page for keyword-based prompt searching. The History page is significantly updated to group prompts by conversation, creating a more intuitive, threaded view. Implements collapsible sections for conversations and individual messages, and uses `react-markdown` to properly render responses.

chore: Update configurations and add test utilities

Updates .gitignore to exclude new build artifacts and log files. Comments out the mongo-express service in docker-compose.yml. Adds several Python utility scripts for debugging and intercepting network traffic.

pull_request.body:
Add a 'g' group for git commands to the application, within this there are two new commands: branches, and co.

The branches command shows the branches available in the current repository, and optionally searches them. The search is very basic just checking for the search string within the branch name.

The co command uses the same logic as above, you can enter a branch name that you'd like to checkout and it will search branches for a match. If there is only one match, it will just check it out. If there are multiple matches, then it will present an interactive choice where you can use the TUI to select which branch you actually want.

To implement the choices TUI, I used the bubbletea package. This handles the interactivity for the app.

To implement the git commands, it is using the exec package, but i introduced a service within the hostsys package to abstract this a bit and avoid some duplication each time we need to call execute a tool in the system.

While doing this I also introduced a logging package that we can use to configure log levels throughout the app. As most of this is a kind of TUI, the errors are presented anyway so the log level by default is a custom "none" level that won't show anything. This log level is a persistent flag that can be changed on each command and will show more errors if needed for debugging.

**What this PR does / why we need it**:
The nightly build fails from time to time on unit tests, when trying to create dashboard handlers based on a non-exists directory of dashboard yamls.

The directory name is computed with:
```go
dir := path.Join(os.TempDir(), fmt.Sprint(time.Now().UTC().Unix()))
```

This pattern is used in two additional unit tests. The guess is that the directory is aleady exist, when the tests assumes it isn't.

This commit gives a unique directory name for each one of the tests that uses the temp directory name pattern, to ensure each test is using its own directory. Also, try to make these test more robust, by taking logic out of the `By` functions, and by adding some error checks.

I'm a longtime node-canvas user but new to the internals. I found this reference to `PANGO_LANGUAGE` and `%PANGO_SCRIPT_HAN` https://github.com/gtk-rs/gir-files/blob/main/Pango-1.0.gir#L11631

pull_request.title: Implement build-push workflow for Aliyun Container Registry with latest stable GitHub Actions
pull_request.body:
This PR implements a new GitHub Actions workflow `build-push.yml` that builds and pushes Docker images to Aliyun Container Registry when changes are pushed to the main branch.

## Key Features

- **Automatic triggering**: Activates on pushes to `main` branch and supports manual dispatch
- **Conditional building**: Uses file change detection to only build when `api/**` or workflow files are modified
- **Latest stable actions**: Updates all GitHub Actions to their newest stable versions for improved security and performance
- **Registry integration**: Seamlessly integrates with Aliyun Container Registry using environment variables and secrets

## Technical Implementation

The workflow consists of two main jobs:

1. **Change Detection**: Uses `dorny/paths-filter@v3` to detect relevant file changes
2. **Build and Push**: Conditionally builds and pushes the API Docker image using the latest Docker actions

## Action Version Updates

All GitHub Actions have been updated to their latest stable versions:
- `actions/checkout@v3` → `@v4`
- `docker/setup-buildx-action@v2` → `@v3` 
- `docker/login-action@v2` → `@v3`
- `docker/metadata-action@v4` → `@v5`
- `docker/build-push-action@v4` → `@v6`
- `dorny/paths-filter@v2` → `@v3`

## Environment Configuration

The workflow requires the following environment variables to be configured in the repository:

**Repository Variables:**
- `ALIYUN_REGISTRY` - Aliyun container registry URL
- `API_IMAGE_NAME` - Target image name

**Repository Secrets:**
- `ALIYUN_REGISTRY_USER` - Registry username
- `ALIYUN_REGISTRY_PWD` - Registry password

## Workflow Relationship

This new workflow complements the existing `only-build.yml` workflow:
- `only-build.yml`: Builds (but doesn't push) on non-main branches
- `build-push.yml`: Builds and pushes on main branch

This ensures a complete CI/CD pipeline where feature branches are validated through build-only testing, while the main branch automatically deploys to the container registry.

Fixes #46.
